properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A wintery mix of precipitation is expected for southern Manitoba beginning Friday and lasting into Sunday. Another Colorado low will cross the northern plains starting early Friday bringing periods of snow and freezing drizzle to southern Manitoba. The mix of precipitation will begin in the southwest spreading eastward throughout the morning. There will be the potential for prolonged periods of freezing drizzle leading to icy conditions on sidewalks and roadways, though exact timing and duration remain uncertain at this time. This mix of precipitation will continue through late Saturday in most areas. Precipitation will then shift over to mainly snow by late Saturday as the system tracks across the Dakotas. Current indications have the heaviest snow and strongest winds in the United States. However, areas along the international border and escarpment may see snowfall totals by Sunday morning exceed 10 cm along with reduced visibilities in blowing snow. The system will depart the area entirely by midday Sunday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected to develop. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Conditions will be favourable for the development of snow squalls from Friday morning to Saturday morning. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Potential for significant snowfall and strong winds Friday night through Sunday morning. Locations: along the coast from L'Anse-au-Clair to Hopedale and inland to Upper Lake Melville. Snowfall totals: possibly 15 to 30 cm. Time span: beginning Friday night and ending overnight Saturday night or Sunday. Remarks: Periods of rain, drizzle and snow are expected to continue along the Labrador coast today and Friday. On Friday night, the precipitation will intensify. It is too soon to accurately predict snowfall totals but at this time, it appears the heaviest accumulations will occur north of the Straits area. A snowfall warning has been issued for Postville to Makkovik for a separate system currently affecting the area. Peak wind gusts: Possibly 90 to 120 km/h. Time span: Saturday morning to Sunday morning. Remarks: Winds will strengthen out of the northeast on Friday night and potentially reach warning criteria by early Saturday. Strong wind gusts will continue and gradually shift to northwesterly by Saturday night. Coastal areas will have the greatest chance of seeing the strongest wind gusts. Specific locations for strongest gusts will be provided in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
